args: People called her the songstress of the century.\nLucretia: The apex of the entire singing world—\na muse with a voice as clear and pure as a bell.
She was beautiful in song.\nShe was beautiful in combat.\nShe was like the heroine of an opera.
Everyone admired her above all other musicians,\nand her fame and reputation were eternal.\nOr so it was thought...
I am no longer a songstress!
I am no longer a songstress.
Bwa ha ha! Good one, Lucretia.\nReal funny prank. Here, lemme make\nsome armpit fart noises to help ya out.
There's no way THE Lucretia would just\nup and stop singin' like that.
I assure you, sir, this is no jest.\nI mean what I said.
Wait. So yer really givin' it up?\nLike, REALLY really?
I can scarce imagine the commotion your\nimpending retirement will cause.
I hear your recitals are quite popular.
Popular's puttin' it lightly. Fancy noble\ntypes practically go to WAR to get a\nticket to one'a her performances.
Whole families have been known to\ncompete with each other for tickets,\nor even flat-out steal 'em.
Sooo...why do you want to give it up?
Nothing in particular, no. I just decided\nI have had enough of this life.
Not that it makes much difference—my\nupcoming performances have all been\ncanceled already.
I imagine that's going to cause quite the\nstir among ticketholders.
Perhaps—or perhaps not. Either way,\nit's nothing to do with me any more.
Some members of an orchestra want to\nspeak with you, {player_name}.
They claim they were scheduled to\nperform with her at her next recital,\nbut then she suddenly disappeared.
Huh? But Lucretia told us her upcoming\nrecitals had all been canceled.
Bwaaa ha ha! I get it now.
They were never REALLY canceled—that\nwas somethin' ya decided on yer own,\nwasn't it?
Which is why the orchestra members are\nso very desperate to find her.
What should I tell them, Lucretia?\nWe can't simply keep them waiting.
Tell them...that I am not here!\nYes, that's it.
They do seem deeply troubled by your\ndisappearance.
Even so! Tell them I am away.
Let's just do what she wants, Cleo.
Well, this is a real mess.
Even if I had told them what I was\nthinking, they wouldn't have allowed it.
They would never have accepted my\nwanting to leave this life.
Why are you so desperate to quit, anyway?
I simply don't wish to sing any more.
I'll do anything you need in its place.\nCleaning, cooking, fiend-pummeling...
So long as it's not singing, you may ask\nanything of me! Pray just allow me to stay\nhere—I beg it of you!
In fact, until you say yes, I will not move\nfrom this spot!
What shall we do, Your Highness?
Please. This is the only place where I can\ntruly get away from singing.
All right, then. You can stay.
Ya sure about this? Ain't no way we're\ngonna be able to hide the world's most\nfamous singer here for long.
I agree. A lot of people are going to be\nvery worried.
I know. But right now, I think we need to\nprioritize Lucretia's feelings.
I don't know what happened to make her\nfeel this way, but it's clear SOMETHING\nis worrying her.
I think we should do what we can to help.
Hee hee! Oh, I can hardly wait to see what\nnew experiences life has in store for me!
Sure don't look like she's worried.
Indeed. Still, I wonder what changes\nhaving the songstress of the century in\nthe Halidom will bring about...
